deck: He is known for Angels and Airwaves and being the former front man of the punk-rock band Blink 182. Tom has written several books and comic books.
description:
Early life

Thomas Matthew Delonge Jr. was born in Poway, California in December 13, 1975. His father was an oil company executive while his mother was a mortgage broker. Tom's first musical instrument was a trumpet which he got for Christmas.

He attended Poway High school but was expelled during the second half of his junior year for coming to a basketball game while inebriated. He moved to Rancho Bernardo High School. This was where he met future band mates Scott Raynor and Mark Hoppus.

Film

After directing a music video for Taking Back Sunday in 2004, DeLonge was fascinated by filmaking calling the process "so artistically satisfying". In 2014 Tom co-directed Poet Anderson: The Dream Walker. Back in 2011, DeLonge's band Angels and Airwaves produced and scored a science fiction drama film called Love. The movie was directed by William Eubank.

Writing

In December 2013, DeLonge released a children's book called The Lonely Astronaut in Christmas Eve. He participated in a charity having Rady Children't Hospital Foundation allowing fans to bid on a package including the book.

The three issue series titled Poet Anderson: The Dream Walker was published by The Magnetic Press in April 2015. The comic book series is based on his award winning short of the same name.

In October 2015, DeLonge released the novel Poet Anderson:... Of Nightmares which was written by him and NY Times Best Selling Author, Suzanne Young. The book was accompanied by an Angels and Airwaves EP called Chasing Shadows.

Musical Influences

Panic! At the Disco's Brandon Urie and Ryan Ross both praised Tom as one of they major influences.
name: Tom DeLonge

description: Furio Arrasich (born 1934) moved to Rome in the ‘50’s. He began his literary career as a crime reporter for daily newspapers, and as an author of detective stories for the publishing house Cofedit. In 1964, he created Fantax, his first comic character, who was soon joined by Demoniak, Dany Coler, and Alika. After Cofedit’s closing, he worked on the comics Zorro, Geronimo, and Johnny Manila for Ceretti. He was appointed director of the weekly series Menelik in 1971, and debuted the comic Maghella, first designed by Dino Leonetti, and later by Mario Janni. After its transfer to the publisher Cavedon, Maghella went from a monthly to a biweekly periodical, resulting in 140 issues published from 1974 to 1981. In 1972, Arrasich collaborated with Cavedon to write Peter Paper, a series created by Pippo Franco and designed by Raul Buzzelli. He launched Sorchella in 1974, and wrote for various comics, including Jacula, E.P, Risate, Racconti Stellari, and Pippo. In 1982, he left comics to become an editor, a postal historian, and a collector of vintage postcards.
name: Furio Arrasich
